\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 7. L. chalcedonicum} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 302 (1753). Stem 45-120 cm. Leaves lanceolate to obovate, 3- to 5-veined, pubescent on the veins beneath, ciliate; lower leaves up to 12 × 2 cm, patent, markedly distinct from the appressed upper leaves, which are not more than 4·5 × 1·5 cm. Flowers 1-7(-12), sometimes bracteolate; pedicels recurved. Perianth-segments 6·5-7 cm, recurved, orange-red, without spots, with papillae inside on lower half. Filaments pale yellow; anthers red. {\i Rocky mountain woods. • S. & W. Greece, S. Albania.} Al Gr.
\par
\par
\pard\f0\fs28  Plants with shorter stems 45-60 cm, usually ebracteolate flowers and with less prominent leaf-cilia have been called {\b L. heldreichii} Freyn,{\i  Flora} ({\i Regensb}.) {\b 63}: 28 (1880). It has a more north-westerly range and{\i  L. chalcedonicum} sensu stricto a more south-easterly range, but the area of overlap is large and the differences are not sufficient to warrant subspecific treatment.
